[[File:Kraftwerk Reisholz um 1930.jpg|thumb|[[Reisholz Power station]] at 1930, between the chimneys one of the two poles]]
'''Reisholz Rhine Powerline Crossing''' is a powerline crossing of Rhine River in [[Düsseldorf]] south of Holthausen substation, which was built in 1917 and originally part of the 110 kV-line between Reisholz Power Station and Goldenberg Power Station. This line was the first 110 kV-powerline of RWE. Later the line was transformed into a 220 kV line with 12 conductors arranged in 4 levels in an unusual double [[Two-level pylon|danube pylon]] mode.
The span width between the pylons, which are both {{convert|88|m|ft}} tall, is {{convert|375|m|ft}}. 
The pylon on the east side of Rhine River has a unique feature as under its legs a normal-gauge railway connecting Holthausen substation with the railway grid passes.

